  "opinion": "As a woman in my 40s who’s spent most of my career as a barista in Washington DC, I’ve seen firsthand how the gender gap in science isn’t just a statistic—it’s a lived reality for so many. I’ve worked with colleagues who’ve been inspired by scientists who look like them, but I’ve also seen how systemic barriers make it harder for women to enter and stay in STEM fields. The gap isn’t just about numbers; it’s about who gets to shape the future. My parents had different educational paths—my mother had a lower secondary education, while my father earned a bachelor’s degree—but even with that, they didn’t grow up in a world where science was a natural fit for women. Back then, it was a field dominated by men, and that mindset still lingers. I’ve noticed that in my community, many young women are hesitant to pursue science because they feel like they don’t belong. It’s not about lack of talent—it’s about the environment. We need to address this gap not by imposing solutions from the outside, but by creating spaces where women feel seen and supported. For me, that means mentoring young women who are curious but unsure, helping them see that science isn’t a solitary pursuit but a community. It’s also about challenging stereotypes in our own communities, especially in places like Washington DC where there’s a rich history of activism. I believe we should address the gender gap in science because it’s a matter of fairness and innovation. If we don’t include diverse perspectives, we’ll miss out on the best ideas. And the way to do it? Start small—by listening, by creating safe spaces, by showing up for each other.",
